sff. Colcha: a standing epi- thet, as Medea, whose home was Colchis, was chief of sorceresses. cf Epod. 5, 243 17, 35. —trac- tavit: has laad α finger 2n; ex- tended by a slight zeugma from venena to quicquid nefas. For this meaning, cf. Epod. 3, 8.

11 f. triste lignum: fatal leg. Cf. 3, 4, 27 devota arbom· and Verg. E. 3, 80 triste lupus stabulis. N early the same meaning appears 2, 14, 8 tristi unda, said of the Styx—te . . . te: the anaphora shows the poet's earnestness.—- caducum ε ready tofall. — domini ε owner, showing that Horace's escape took place on his own farm.
